    <description>The Harlan J. Smith 2.7-meter Telescope is a prominent optical telescope located at McDonald Observatory in West Texas. Completed in 1968, it was the third-largest telescope in the world at the time and remains a key instrument for astronomical research. The telescope is equipped with multiple focal points, including Cassegrain, Ritchey-Chrétien, and Coudé configurations, and supports a variety of instruments such as the George and Cynthia Mitchell Spectrograph (GCMS) and the Visible Integral-field Replicable Unit Spectrograph-W (VIRUS-W). Notably, it has contributed to significant discoveries, including the detection of a supermassive black hole in the Leo 1 dwarf galaxy.
